What an incredible lunch visit from these two awesome people @kendrick_bbq @chosen_1_bbq!  When Bennie scheduled lunch, I assumed we’d eat some quick take-out in my office.  What arrived was one of the most incredible meals I’ve ever eaten, and certainly more protein than any human should eat in one sitting!  Adding to the special lunch, Paul came bearing a gift that absolutely blew my mind - @solesbysir hand painted Nike shoes that reflect perfectly my love for Traeger and our community.  These babies only get worn on special occasions!

As Bennie and Paul left, I was thinking about how many great friendships I’ve made over the years through this incredible Traeger community.  I remember the first time I saw a post from Bennie on Instagram many years ago and have loved watching him grow and accomplish great things.  He’s become a dear friend.  I also connected with Paul on social media and met him for the first time when he flew out to Utah for Traeger day in May.  Awesome human being, great Traeger story and happy to call him a friend.  The Traegerhood is alive and well and really adds richness to my life every day.

PS. @deluxebbq your home grown honey was pure gold on the grilled brussel spouts!  We missed you, my friend!

Seven years ago this crew of entrepreneurs set off on our first adventure trip backpacking around cold, rainy Yosemite National Park.  Each year we trek to some interesting spot and rough it in the wilderness.  We’ve hiked mountains, spear fished (with some hungry days without success!), dropped in the middle of the Amazon, etc.  Each trip has its own character and lessons learned.

This year we climbed three breathtaking mountains in Ecuador.  Mount Cotopaxi only allowed us to go to 17k feet to the glacier as it was literally erupting as we climbed.  Each trip has a moment where I feel exhasted, sore, hungry, uncomfortable or even scared (I don’t love heights, jaguars near camp or cuts from alligator). I mostly love the adventure and beauty of the remote places we visit, but every once in a while I ask myself, ‘what am I doing here?’ A couple of years ago I published an article that answers this question (link in bio).

While the genisis of these trips was adventure, the real joy has evolved into strengthening friendships with some of the best human beings I know.  We talk fatherhood, marriage, family, career, life aspirations, weaknesses, disappointments and successes.  Every year I leave feeling like the quality of conversation over the course of the week has made me better, stronger, more resolute, more inspired and fully recharged for whatever lies ahead when I return. 

I’m grateful for these experiences. I never would have imagined from our first Yosemite trip that these adventures would one day become so meaningful to me.  Thank you fellas!

What an evening with my @traegergrills peeps!  Took home ‘Product of the Year’ award for the new Timberline launched last year.  Big shout out to the Product team for developing such an incredible, powerful and elegant outdoor cooking machine. It’s the best there is!  And my heartfelt appreciation to every member of our entire team who helped bring this product to market.  Always a team effort - proud of you all!

The evening was extra special as I had the honor of introducing my good friend, Jonathan Johnson (CEO Overstock), who was inducted into the Silicon Slopes Hall of Fame.  He’s someone I have admire deeply for years and was happy to be part of his well deserved recognition.  Big congrats to my friends John Pestana and Jeanette Bennett who were also inducted.  All three have contributed so much good to our community.  Truly grateful for them.

Finding words to do justice to this past week isn’t easy. We trekked a full 30 hours with our six kiddos in tow to ultimately land in a village of 72 homes speckled in a remote mountain village in Nepal. We came with @choiceorg (who is amazing btw) to spend time with and serve the people who live here. We dug trenches and laid pipe for what will ultimately provide fresh water to a town that has not had access. We painted the school whose floors we slept on. We purchased and assembled hygiene kits and taught the children how to wash their bodies and brush their teeth. Kristin and the girls brought period products and educated young women on menstruation. 

We came to serve. As we leave, I’m sure we barely moved the needle for this village, and I’m grateful that the Choice team will stay to finish. But I leave feeling like we enriched our lives and developed perspective that was so much more valuable than what we leave behind. As we worked and played alongside these local villagers, our family made friends, developed a perspective on humble living, observed happiness as well as pain in the plight of poverty, saw progress and the value of education, experiences human connection amongst people who didn’t speak the same language, and felt appreciation for the comforts we have back home. Now we can’t wait for a shower, a bed, a toilet and some clean clothes.

#grateful #teamandrus

Many years ago my view on being a father changed as I read ’Strong Fathers Strong Daughters’ by @megmeekermd.  I could barely get through a page without tears in my eyes as I thought about how important my role is as a dad in helping my daughters grow to realize their full potential.

Years have passed since I read that book, but the same flood of emotions came back this weekend as I spent three days with my daughters at GirlDad camp at BYU.  We played sports, wandered out on long walks, talked endlessly, listened to inspiring speeches from impressive fathers, mothers and daughters and reconnected on a level that fueled my desire to be a better dad.  I want my daughters to be strong, confident, secure, driven and kind. Like their mama.  I believe in them!

#girldad

As I was preparing thoughts to share in our all-hands company meeting today, I reached out to a good friend who was commander of Hill Air Force Base a few years ago.  I asked if he would share his feelings on the significance of 9.11 to our country from the perspective of someone who gave his career to the country.  He’s a leader and a patriot I respect tremendously.  His work touched me and I wanted to share it here.

I’ll never forget the moment - sitting in a business school class in Boston - when I first heard the news that something very serious and scary was happening.  Our country was under attack on our own soil.  It took some time to sort out exactly what was going on and how it would change our country.

As horrible as the moment was, I cherish the unity I felt as an American. Heroes put their lives at risk as they came to the rescue - firefighters, policeman, medical personnel, even ordinary citizens.  As a people, we put aside our usual petty, political bickering and rallied around everything we believed in as a country.  The free world came together and supported us in a trying time.  During a period of fear and insecurity, I felt strength and optimism in our collective efforts.

I’ve always been proud to be an American and was raised to deeply value the freedoms this country has afforded us.  Every time I put my hand to my heart to say the Pledge of Allegiance or sing our national anthem, I am reminded of this moment 22 years ago today and feel a greater desire to contribute to our future any way I can.

#neverforget #nineeleven
